  1. **Two genuine WebKit-only bugs**, chromium/firefox both pass the
     identical assertions: (a) `e2e/offlineSession.msw.spec.ts:46` — a
     failed intercepted request under WebKit's own service worker raises
     a real in-page error event Chromium/Firefox don't raise the same
     way; (b) `e2e/offlineShell.spec.ts:21` — `page.reload()` while
     offline throws a WebKit-internal error before the precache can even
     be exercised. Neither fixed yet — flagged forward for
     `senior-frontend-developer` triage, since tester's job is to find,
     not fix.
  2. **A live production reliability issue, independently confirmed
     three separate times** (once by the orchestrating session's own
     `curl` probing before dispatch even completed, once by 6E, once by
     6A): `POST /api/v1/search` against the real Render backend
     intermittently returns HTTP 502 in under 1.5s, and when it does
     succeed can take 30-46s — this while `/health` stays consistently
     fast and green throughout. Ruled out as an application bug by
     reading the actual code: PubMed/iCite calls are correctly
     `httpx.AsyncClient`-based, the outbound rate limiter uses
     `asyncio.sleep` not a blocking call. This points to a genuine Render
     free-tier infra/capacity issue (leading hypothesis: single Uvicorn
     worker with no `--workers` flag in `render.yaml`, possibly combined
     with `NCBI_API_KEY` not actually being set in production dropping
     outbound pacing to 3 req/s) — needs the human to check Render's
     dashboard (restart/memory logs, confirm `NCBI_API_KEY` is set),
     since no agent has dashboard access. One genuine silver lining: when
     a decision failed to save because of this, the app correctly fell
     back to its "pending — will retry" offline UI instead of losing the
     swipe — that resilience path works as designed.
